  <content>
    <title>Django Models</title>

    <summary>Django model design following the BaseModel abstract pattern (integer PK + UUID field + timestamps), with explicit on_delete on every ForeignKey, TextChoices enums in per-app constants.py, and composite Meta.indexes for query-driven indexing. Django 5 db_default is supported for database-computed defaults.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>A consistent BaseModel base eliminates timestamp/UUID boilerplate and gives every record a stable external identifier (uid) separate from the internal integer PK. Explicit on_delete prevents accidental data loss. TextChoices centralizes enum values so admin, forms, and serializers share one source. Declaring indexes in Meta.indexes keeps them reviewable in migrations.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Creating a new Django app's models/ package.</item>
        <item>Refactoring ad-hoc models to the canonical BaseModel + Meta.indexes shape.</item>
        <item>Adding ForeignKey relations and choosing on_delete policy.</item>
        <item>Introducing per-app constants.py with TextChoices enums.</item>
        <item>Adding Django 5 db_default / computed fields.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Async ORM workflows (.asave(), .aget()) — async manager patterns are not covered here.</item>
        <item>Multi-database routing, sharding, or replicas — out of scope.</item>
        <item>Heavy JSONField / ArrayField document-style data — methodology assumes relational schema.</item>
        <item>Tenant isolation (django-tenants, schema-per-tenant) — needs additional methodology.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="base-model-pattern">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>All domain models must inherit from BaseModel. BaseModel provides integer PK (implicit id), a UUID external identifier (uid), created_at, and updated_at.</statement>
        <rationale>Consistent base eliminates boilerplate. Integer PK is used for internal joins; uid is the stable external identifier exposed to APIs and clients.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="BaseModel with ForeignKey and Indexes">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import uuid
from django.db import models

class BaseModel(models.Model):
    uid = models.UUIDField(default=uuid.uuid4, editable=False, unique=True)
    created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)
    updated_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now=True)

    class Meta:
        abstract = True

class Order(BaseModel):
    user = models.ForeignKey("users.User", on_delete=models.PROTECT)
    amount = models.DecimalField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2)
    status = models.CharField(max_length=20, choices=STATUS_CHOICES)

    class Meta:
        ordering = ["-created_at"]
        indexes = [
            models.Index(fields=["status", "created_at"]),
        ]

    def __str__(self) -> str:
        return f"Order {self.uid}"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/base-model.py">Standalone BaseModel definition.</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="foreign-key-on-delete-policies">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Supply on_delete= explicitly on every ForeignKey. Use PROTECT for data you must not lose, CASCADE only for owned children, SET_NULL for optional references.</statement>
        <rationale>The default is not safe; omitting on_delete causes a migration error in Django 2.0+ and signals unclear intent in code review.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="ForeignKey on_delete Patterns">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# PROTECT — prevent deletion if related exists
user = models.ForeignKey("users.User", on_delete=models.PROTECT)

# CASCADE — delete together (use carefully!)
item = models.ForeignKey("Item", on_delete=models.CASCADE)

# SET_NULL — set to NULL on delete
last_handler = models.ForeignKey(
    "Handler",
    on_delete=models.SET_NULL,
    null=True,
    blank=True,
    related_name="handled_orders",
)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Add related_name= to every ForeignKey. If the reverse accessor is not needed, use related_name='+'.</statement>
        <rationale>Without related_name, Django generates a default name that clashes when two models share a parent, causing migration errors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="meta-indexes">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define all indexes in Meta.indexes with an explicit name following the pattern appname_model_columns_idx. Do not rely on db_index=True for composite indexes.</statement>
        <rationale>Named indexes in Meta.indexes are visible in migrations and reviewable. Pair with EXPLAIN against representative data — don't add indexes speculatively.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use UniqueConstraint(fields=[...], name="...") instead of deprecated unique_together.</statement>
        <rationale>unique_together is deprecated and will be removed in a future Django version.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="django-5-db-default">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use db_default for database-level defaults (computed at INSERT by the DB). Use default= for application-level defaults (computed by Python). Do not mix them.</statement>
        <rationale>db_default generates different SQL migrations and applies at a different layer. Confusing them produces migrations that fail on older DB versions (requires Postgres 12+ / SQLite 3.38+).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Database-Computed Default">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from django.db.models.functions import Now

class Article(models.Model):
    created_at = models.DateTimeField(db_default=Now())
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="text-choices-and-constants">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define all field choices as TextChoices subclasses in a per-app constants.py. Reference them from models, admin, forms, and serializers via the same import.</statement>
        <rationale>Single source of truth prevents drift between the choices used in the model definition and those used in forms/serializers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="TextChoices Pattern">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# apps/users/constants.py
from django.db import models

class UserType(models.TextChoices):
    REGULAR = "regular", "Regular"
    PREMIUM = "premium", "Premium"
    ADMIN = "admin", "Administrator"

DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE = 20
MAX_ITEMS_PER_USER = 100
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Model Using TextChoices">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# apps/users/models/user.py
from apps.users import constants as user_constants

class User(BaseModel):
    user_type = models.CharField(
        max_length=20,
        choices=user_constants.UserType.choices,
        default=user_constants.UserType.REGULAR,
    )
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Import constants using the module alias pattern: from apps.users import constants as user_constants. Do not do from apps.users.constants import UserType.</statement>
        <rationale>Module alias makes the origin explicit at call sites and prevents ambiguous name collisions when multiple apps have a UserType.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/constants.py">Per-app constants.py template.</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="project-structure">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Each app follows the standard structure with models/, services/, tests/, constants.py, and migrations/. Split models into individual files under models/ for apps with more than 2 models.</statement>
        <rationale>Flat models.py becomes unwieldy; splitting into models/user.py, models/order.py keeps each file focused and reduces merge conflicts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Project Layout">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
project/
├── config/
│   ├── settings/
│   │   ├── base.py
│   │   ├── development.py
│   │   └── production.py
│   ├── urls.py
│   └── celery.py
├── apps/
│   ├── users/
│   ├── orders/
│   └── catalog/
├── core/
│   ├── models.py     <- BaseModel lives here
│   └── exceptions.py
└── tests/
    └── conftest.py
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Per-App Structure">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
users/
├── models/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   └── user.py
├── services/
├── utils/
├── tasks/
├── admin/
├── serializers/
├── views/
├── filters/
├── migrations/
├── constants.py
├── apps.py
├── urls.py
└── tests/
    ├── conftest.py
    ├── unit/
    └── integration/
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Treat model changes as propose-diff → migration-review → test. Have one subagent draft the model edit, a second run manage.py makemigrations --dry-run --check and inspect the auto-generated migration file for destructive ops (RemoveField, AlterField on PKs, RenameField). A third subagent writes/updates a pytest fixture covering the new field's choices and constraints. Never let a single agent both edit models and generate migrations without a review gate.</p>
      <p>Model generation subagent constraints: extend BaseModel (UUID+timestamps); FK on_delete must be explicit; choices live in constants.py as TextChoices. After edit: run python manage.py makemigrations --dry-run and paste the planned migration. Stop and ask before running with --no-dry-run if any field is removed/renamed.</p>
      <p>Index-adding subagent: Add an index for the query pattern. Use Meta.indexes; name it app_model_cols_idx. Do not drop other indexes. Output the migration plan only.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Agents may switch the PK to UUID by replacing id with uid — the pattern keeps integer PK + indexed UUID. Re-state this in the prompt or it will produce an irreversible migration.</p>
      <p>auto_now=True / auto_now_add=True are silently ignored by bulk_create and update(). Agents writing batch jobs often miss this.</p>
      <p>db_default and default look interchangeable but produce different migrations and apply at different layers (DB vs Python). Agents conflate them.</p>
      <p>LLMs love adding unique=True on email / username without db_index=False — Postgres makes uniqueness an index, so explicit db_index=True is redundant; agents add both.</p>
      <p>Human-in-loop checkpoint: review every generated migration's operations = [...] before migrate. Especially watch for AlterField that changes column type — Postgres may rewrite the table.</p>
      <p>Agents often add new choice values to TextChoices and forget the migration — choices are stored in DB enums only if you opt into them; otherwise just code-level.</p>
      <p>Do not let an agent run migrate --fake autonomously; it desyncs the migration graph from schema.</p>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Identify all entities and relationships</check>
      <check>Determine field types and constraints for each entity</check>
      <check>Plan ForeignKey on_delete behavior for each relationship</check>
      <check>Identify fields that need indexes (FK fields, frequently filtered fields)</check>
      <check>Plan timestamped fields (use BaseModel)</check>
      <check>Create BaseModel abstract class in core/models.py if not present</check>
      <check>Define all models inheriting from BaseModel</check>
      <check>Add field validators and help_text for non-obvious fields</check>
      <check>Define __str__ methods</check>
      <check>Create custom QuerySets for common filters</check>
      <check>Add Meta options: ordering, indexes, db_table names</check>
      <check>Put all TextChoices in constants.py</check>
      <check>Define ForeignKey with explicit on_delete</check>
      <check>Add related_name= on every FK (use '+' if reverse not needed)</check>
      <check>Use lazy string references ('app.Model') to avoid circular imports</check>
      <check>Replace unique_together with UniqueConstraint(fields=[], name="...")</check>
      <check>Verify FK fields have database indexes (Django adds them automatically)</check>
      <check>Add composite indexes to Meta.indexes for common filter combinations</check>
      <check>Name every index: appname_model_cols_idx</check>
      <check>Remove redundant db_index=True when uniqueness already implies an index</check>
      <check>Run makemigrations --check to detect unstaged model changes</check>
      <check>Review migration operations for destructive changes (RemoveField, AlterField on PKs)</check>
      <check>Test migration on a fresh database before committing</check>
      <check>Never edit applied migration files; create a new migration instead</check>
    </checklist>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/base-model.py" purpose="Abstract BaseModel with UUID + timestamps."/>
      <template path="templates/constants.py" purpose="Per-app constants.py with TextChoices enum example."/>
      <template path="templates/check-migrations.sh" purpose="Pre-commit script: refuse commit if model changed without staged migration."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
